TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Competitive Effects of Trust-Busting: A Portfolio Analysis
AU  - Burns, Malcolm R.
Y1  - 1977/08/01
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260597
DO  - 10.1086/260597
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 717
EP  - 739
VL  - 85
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Monthly stock prices are used to analyze the competitive effects of the Sherman Act dissolutions carried out against Standard Oil, American Tobacco, and American Snuff on December 1, 1911. Statistical tests of the price changes accompanying important developments in the litigation show rather strongly that investors did not expect dissolution to alter the performance of the snuff, tobacco, and petroleum industries. This conclusion is similar to the findings of previous studies of these cases, and the results indicate that applications of stock prices and finance theory can significantly augment the empirical research methods of industrial organization.
AB  - Monthly stock prices are used to analyze the competitive effects of the Sherman Act dissolutions carried out against Standard Oil, American Tobacco, and American Snuff on December 1, 1911. Statistical tests of the price changes accompanying important developments in the litigation show rather strongly that investors did not expect dissolution to alter the performance of the snuff, tobacco, and petroleum industries. This conclusion is similar to the findings of previous studies of these cases, and the results indicate that applications of stock prices and finance theory can significantly augment the empirical research methods of industrial organization.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260597
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260597
Y2  - 2024/03/22
